WEST NILE FEVER VIRUS, LEMURS - MADAGASCAR (03)
===============================================
Date: Sat, 10 May 1997 08:58:29 +0200
From: Jacques Morvan <morvan@intnet.cf>
See Also
West Nile Fever virus, lemurs - Madagascar: RFI 970508191233
West Nile Fever virus, lemurs - Madagascar (02) 970509172009
West Nile virus is widely distributed throughout Africa, Asia and Europe.
In Madagascar, West Nile virus has been isolated from human blood, birds
(parrots _Coracopsis vasa_, and egrets _Bulbicus ibis_) and from several
mosquito species (_Culex decens_, _Cx. quinquefasciatus_, _Cx.
tritaeniorhynchus_, _Cx. antennatus_, _Cx._ univittatus_, _Aedes
albocephalus_, _Ae. circumluteolus_, _Ae. aegypti_, _Ae. madagascarensis_,
_Anopheles brunnipes_, _An. maculipalpis_). Clinical syndrome classically
associated with West Nile infection of humans [manifests as an acute,
febrile illness. Encephalitis may be commun [i.e., more common than generally
recognized?.
In Central African Republic (1983), four cases of fatal hepatitis [due to
West Nile virus infection were confirmed by virus isolation from blood and
liver biopsies. Also in CAR, the virus has been isolated from several local
birds (brown-crowned tchagra, black-crowned waxbill) and several mosquito
genera (_Aedes_, _Culex_, and _Mansonia_).
